1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
This is DeepSeek V4 Flash, a 284-billion-parameter Mixture-of-Experts model.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:14,000
The GGUF file used here is about 150 gigabytes on Hugging Face.

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:21,000
The machine is a 64 gigabyte M1 Max.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:31,000
So the question is not just whether the machine can compute the model.
It is whether the operating system can bring the right expert weights into memory at the right time.

5
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:41,000
Dense models tend to reuse the same mapped weight ranges during decode.
DeepSeek V4 Flash is different.

6
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:50,000
It routes each token through a changing subset of experts, so decode can become dominated by page-in latency.

7
00:00:50,000 --> 00:01:00,000
The benchmark model is lovedheart slash DeepSeek-V4-Flash-GGUF, using the MXFP4_MOE GGUF file.

8
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:08,000
The model file itself is not included in GitHub. The repository includes scripts, patches, charts, and reproduction notes.

9
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:18,000
For the video, I show live token generation so viewers can see the local model actually producing text.

10
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:28,000
The optimization is intentionally small. The model stays mmap-backed, and CPU repacking is disabled.

11
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:40,000
After the MoE router chooses the active experts, the runtime calls MADV_WILLNEED on those expert matrix ranges.

12
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:49,000
The operating system still owns the file-backed cache, so pages remain reclaimable.

13
00:01:49,000 --> 00:02:00,000
The clean decode comparison uses the same model, the same prompts, and no static prewarm in either case.

14
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:09,000
With the expert page hint disabled, decode generation averaged 0.98 tokens per second.

15
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:18,000
With routing-aware MADV_WILLNEED enabled, it averaged 1.23 tokens per second.

16
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:26,000
That is a 25.4 percent throughput gain without changing the model.

17
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:37,000
The long-run data also showed that prefill and decode should be optimized differently.

18
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:48,000
Prefill behaves like broad layer-level page-in throughput. Decode is more latency-sensitive.

19
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:59,000
That is why a single global cache policy is probably not enough for this kind of model.

20
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:11,000
The repository includes parser artifacts, benchmark data, charts, and a rebuild process for the packed expert export.

21
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:24,000
This is not a claim that a 64 gigabyte machine is the ideal way to run a model this large.

22
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:38,000
It is a demonstration that for sparse MoE models, local inference is often about memory residency and page-in timing, not just raw compute.

23
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:48,000
MoE-MADV means Mixture-of-Experts plus MADV_WILLNEED.

24
00:03:48,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The project is available at github.com slash daystar7777 slash MoE-MADV.
